ce>ES/F034725/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>Primary science classroom practitioners and government-sanctioned educational policy generally advocate the use of open questions for elicitation.&amp;nbsp; In general, however, Diane?s doctoral research found that open questions are used less often and less successfully with younger children and an explanation for this was found in sociocultural notions of acculturation into a community of scientific discourse.
&lt;br />
&lt;br />One of the aims of the Postdoctoral Fellowship is therefore to reach out to policy communities with the findings of the PhD research, encouraging a policy re-think in the UK and internationally. 
&lt;br />
&lt;br />In addition, further training in quantitative research methods will enable Diane to complete additional analyses of the data collected during her doctoral research. The development of these skills, including those employed in her doctorate, will lead to two significant contributions to knowledge:
&lt;br />
&lt;br />
&lt;ol>
 &lt;li>an explanation of the reasons why significant numbers of open questions prove 'unsuccessful' from the teachers' scientific perspective.&lt;/li>
 &lt;li>the identification of cohesion (Halliday &amp;amp; Hasan, 1976) as a significant factor in determining whether teachers? questions prove to be successful/unsuccessful in terms of the creation of a scientific narrative from the classroom discourse.&lt;/li>
&lt;/ol>
&lt;br />&amp;nbsp;
